<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALL SDG&amp;E DIRECTORS, EXCEPT 1, ARE SAN DIEGANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With the exception of one Los Angeles resident, the seven members of San Diego 
Gas &amp; Electric's board of directors are San Diegans. Members of the largely 
home-grown group are active in local business, civic and charitable circles. 
</P>
<P>
* Clair W. Burgener, 68, a director since 1983, is president of a local real 
estate development firm. He is a former Republican Congressman from La Jolla. 
</P>
<P>
* Malin Burnham, 62, is director of a financial services firm and chairman of 
First National Corp., a local bank-holding company. Burnham is active in many 
local organizations, including the San Diego Yacht Club, and organized the 
successful America's Cup challenge that brought the cup to San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
* Daniel W. Derbes, 59, a director since 1983, was an executive with Signal 
Cos., the La Jolla-based company that in 1985 agreed to be acquired by New 
Jersey-based Allied Corp. Derbes also served as a board member of Oak 
Industries, which recently agreed to move its corporate headquarters to New 
England. 
</P>
<P>
* Ralph R. Ocampo, 58, a director since 1983, is a physician and surgeon in San 
Diego. He is a director of Mercy Hospital, and is active in several local 
charitable and professional organizations. 
</P>
<P>
* Fred C. Stalder, 69, a member of the board since 1969, was chief executive 
officer of Central Federal Savings &amp; Loan a now-defunct thrift in San 
Diego. Now retired, Stalder has been active in many local organizations for 40 
years. 
</P>
<P>
* Catherine Fitzgerald Wiggs, 56, a director since 1979, is the only 
out-of-town board member. Wiggs is a management consultant who previously 
served as an executive vice president at The Broadway Stores. 
</P>
<P>
* Thomas A. Page, 56, a director since 1979, has been chairman of the board 
since 1983. He is a past chairman of the San Diego Economic Development 
Commission, which has opposed the merger. SDG&amp;E recently dropped its 
membership in the Greater San Diego Chamber of Commerce, which also has opposed 
the merger. 
</P>
