<HEADLINE>
<P>
RED STAR FALLING IN SMALLEST REPUBLIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN MARINO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The winds of change sweeping Eastern Europe have finally reached the world's 
smallest republic, whose Communists -- 1,100 of them -- are preparing to change 
the name and politics of their party. 
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of the Republic of San Marino, believed to be the world's 
smallest legally recognized Marxist grouping, will discard its name and its red 
star, hammer and sickle logo at a party congress next month. 
</P>
<P>
The party of the tiny, landlocked republic in northern Italy, which represents 
29% of San Marino's 23,000 residents, probably will be called the Progressive 
Democratic Party, a social democratic grouping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
