<HEADLINE>
<P>
RUNNING; 
</P>
<P>
PADILLA BREAKS U.S. RECORD, BUT NO WORLD BEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT MILLER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CARLSBAD 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
All Doug Padilla was trying to do Sunday in the Carlsbad 5,000 men's elite race 
was stay in contention. Nothing more, nothing less. 
</P>
<P>
Pretty simple strategy, really. 
</P>
<P>
"I was just trying to match whatever move anybody made," he said. 
</P>
<P>
What he did was come up with a few moves nobody else made and win in 13:29.50, 
an American 5,000-meter road race record. 
</P>
<P>
Padilla came in just ahead of Mexico's Ignacio Fragoso (13:31) and Kenya's 
Barnaba Korir (13:37). 
</P>
<P>
Elly Van Hulst of Holland won the women's elite race in 15:32.50. PattiSue 
Plumer was second in 15:35 and Annette Peters next in 15:36. 
</P>
<P>
There were an estimated 35,000 spectators. Padilla and Van Hulst each won 
$5,000. 
</P>
<P>
There were no world bests, noteworthy because of the race's history. The men's 
winner has set a world standard in three of the past four years. Two of those 
were by Steve Scott, who was 10th Sunday. Padilla surpassed Scott's American 
mark of 13:30.2. 
</P>
<P>
"This is a real high point," Padilla said. "This is by far the most prestigious 
5K in the world. To come here and have a good race would be great, but to have 
a good race and get the American record is fantastic." 
</P>
<P>
Padilla, 33, lives in Orem, Utah. He completed his eligibility at Brigham Young 
University in 1981 and got a degree in electrical engineering from there in 
1983. He holds the American track record at 3,000 meters, two miles (indoors) 
and 5,000 meters (indoors). He has run well in 1990, winning the indoor track 
circuit's grand prix, after a rough spell last year. 
</P>
<P>
Still, he wasn't sure how he would fare in Carlsbad. He has asthma, and spring 
isn't normally a very good time for that. And, he wasn't happy with his 
performance in Carlsbad last year -- he was so far back in the pack that he 
doesn't even know where he finished. Finally, his wife gave birth to his third 
child two weeks ago, so he hasn't gotten much sleep lately. 
</P>
<P>
He took the lead about 1 1/4 miles into the race and, while never running away, 
fended off the others. 
</P>
<P>
As Padilla approached the two-mile mark, 12 runners were bunched up in a tight 
lead pack. The leaders crossed the two-mile mark in 8:51. Two-and-a-half miles 
in, six runners remained in the lead pack -- but Padilla was ahead. 
</P>
<P>
"I could always hear footsteps," he said. "Two guys came up with me and the 
second turnaround (Carlsbad Blvd./Mountain View Dr.) and I had to push to stay 
up. Down the home stretch, Fragoso was right there." 
</P>
<P>
The second turn-around, though, was crucial. There are two on the course, and 
both are hairpin turns, much tighter than what Padilla is used to on a track. 
</P>
<P>
"One difference is, you can get boxed in on either side in a road race," he 
said. "If you're in the second or third lane on a track, you're never going to 
get boxed in. Last year, I bet I lost 30 yards on the first turnaround." 
</P>
<P>
Once he successfully navigated the second turn Sunday, it was just a question 
of hanging on. 
</P>
<P>
"I could feel that I was starting to get tired. My legs were getting tight 
during the last 400 meters. I could see the finish wasn't very far away. I was 
just hoping to get there before my legs fell apart." 
</P>
<P>
The biggest problem Van Hulst faced in the women's race was at the start. The 
elite men and women ran at the same time, and one of the men got tangled up in 
the crowd at the start and fell in Van Hulst's path. 
</P>
<P>
"I jumped over him," Van Hulst said. "I was just hoping I didn't fall. I think 
I was on the wrong side. I started on the left side. Next year, I'll stay on 
the right side." 
</P>
<P>
Van Hulst, who won the 3,000-meter race at the European Indoor Championships 
and holds the world record for that distance at 8:33, also had to contend with 
a pack, albeit smaller, in the women's race. She, Plumer and Peters were close 
the entire way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, (San Diego County Edition) Doug Padilla (right) was just trying to stay 
in contention, but he beat Mexico's Ignacio Fragoso to the finish line Sunday 
in the Carlsbad 5,000. Padilla's 13:29.50 set the American 5,000-meter road 
race record. DAVID MCNEW / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
