<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE'S PHARMACY: 'RAPE' IN DENTIST'S OFFICE IS MORE LIKELY MERE FANTASY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE GRAEDON, TERESA GRAEDON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I don't know whether my mind has played a trick on me or whether I 
was raped. 
</P>
<P>
I have known my dentist for over 10 years. He is in his 60s, very professional, 
and I always thought he was a gentleman. But last month something happened to 
make me question this. 
</P>
<P>
I had to have oral surgery and he gave me an IV sedative. The procedure was 
done in his office with the door open and the hygienist assisting, but I am 
sure I was sexually assaulted during the procedure. 
</P>
<P>
I asked the hygienist whether she ever left the room and she insisted she was 
there the whole time. She reassured me that nothing happened and that the 
medicine could have made me imagine it. 
</P>
<P>
Can a sedative do that? The experience seemed so real, but I don't want to 
accuse my dentist of rape if it was all in my mind. 
</P>
<P>
Answer: We don't doubt that there have been instances when an unethical health 
professional has taken unfair advantage of a sedated patient. Don't assume, 
however, that your dentist is at fault. 
</P>
<P>
Evidence is mounting that intravenous sedation with benzodiazepines may induce 
sexual fantasies, including disturbing situations like the one you describe. 
One woman even took her dentist to court, despite the fact that her husband had 
been standing next to her throughout the procedure. The husband testified on 
the dentist's behalf. 
</P>
<P>
Anyone undergoing a procedure that requires intravenous sedation should insist 
on having a third person in the room at all times. 
</P>
<P>
With the hygienist present and the door open, it is very unlikely that your 
dentist engaged in any misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
Q. What can you tell me about "Guarana," the concentrated energizer? It is sold 
in health food stores as an herb for energy, mental alertness and as an 
appetite suppressant. 
</P>
<P>
A. Guarana comes from the crushed seeds of a Brazilian shrub. Although it has a 
reputation as an appetite suppressant, aphrodisiac and a stimulant, its active 
ingredient is no more mysterious than caffeine. 
</P>
<P>
It contains 3% to 5% caffeine, about twice as much as coffee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
